Democrats will control the House. That is determined. Control of the Senate comes down to the two run-off races in Georgia, and Democrats need a sweep to take control of both houses of Congress. If we assume even odds in both races (0.5), then there is a one in four chance (0.5 x 0.5 = 0.25) of Democrats sweeping and taking control, and a 3 in four (0.75) chance of Republicans maintaining control of the Senate while Democrats maintain control of the House. The current FiveThirtyEight average has both Democratic candidates maintaining a very slight edge (Warnock +1.6; Ossof +1.0). (https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/georgia-senate-polls/ ). Since even odds here translates to a 75/25 likelihood that Republicans hold the Senate and Democrats the House, I’m going to go with a very slight Democratic advantage and say 70/30.

The only possible outcome at this point is either Democratic or Republican control of the Senate because the Democrats won the House already. Thus, the remaining two special senate races in Georgia are the determinants of this issue as the current balance in the senate will be 46(D) - 50 (R) - 2 (I) [Note the I's caucus with Democrats). The presidential election showed local races still favor the GOP in historically GOP areas (for example Maine), but that the President underperformed local candidates in many areas except when a large Latino population was present (Maine, Georgia). Presidential elections also see higher turnout which generally favors republicans. Loeffler is an unpopular candidate and may lose her reelection (or is it still reelection if you were never elected in the first place?), but Purdue seems unlikely to lose as an incumbent. Further, given that Perdue's failure to secure 50% of the vote in the previous election seems to have been due to a Libertarian candidate (Shane Hazel) and his challenger his fairly socially progressive with respect to Georgia at large. Nevertheless, polls show both senate races in a dead heat (with Perdue slightly ahead of Ossoff and Loeffler tied or slightly behind Warnock), but given that polls have been slightly biased against republicans and democrats have to flip both seats to gain the senate this seems unlikely. I would estimate that the base rate odds of a dead heat race for both are 50-50, but given that Republicans only need one win that is a 25% - 75% ratio for R-D. Factoring in the lower turnout from an off-cycle election, the unpopularity of Loeffler, and the incumbency of Perdue I would estimate the most likely outcome is a Perdue victory and a Warnock victory splitting the Senate 47(D)-51(R)-2(I). The likelihood that democrats unseat Perdue and Loeffler seems low. (15%)

Let's put politics aside. Let's just look at the numbers. Using the House first, and data from the website 270towin.com (https://www.270towin.com/2020-house-election/), we see that 43% of the seats are safe for the Democrats, and 36% for the Republicans; safe meaning districts that are demographically, economically, and are otherwise politically secure bastions for that party. We also see that 9% of the seats in the House are not safe, but lean towards or likely will go to the Democrats, while 8% lean towards the Republicans. That leaves a total of 5% of the seats in the house that could go either way. Barring some kind of tectonic demographic shift, there is just not enough at play in this election to see the Republicans taking back the House. The Republicans would have to win all of the seats that could go either way (5%) plus over half of the seats that lean towards the Democrats (5%), plus not lose any of the unsafe seats. A tall order for the party with an unpopular president.

The way we view polling reminds me of the way we see the stock market... when we're up, we think we'll stay up; when we're down, we think we'll stay down. After all, I don't know how diverse we are (the GJO community.) It takes a pretty specific personality to become a forecasting hobbyist. So, I wonder how much that collectively colors the way we see the world.

I also follow some other news sites (disclosure: I am not American - I am a Canadian living in Hong Kong). 3) I assume (based on my reading of news, polls etc) that there is nearly zero chance that Republicans can win the House. I also assume the fact that Biden is winning in the presidential polls currently means there will be some tendency towards higher Democratic turnout in senate voting. 4) My base rate is betfair betting market which seems to currently give the Dems a 35-40 percent chance of winning a majority in both houses. However, again I am assuming here that “control” by Dems could be 50/50 with a Dem VP elected. For purposes of this question, I give Dems roughly a 65% chance to elect the President VP (which is a bit higher now than, but consistent with, betting markets). 5) I am also aware of a recent prediction of a FiveThirtyEight analyst that the “base case” right now is 51+ Dem senators. So if I average that with the (say) 40% chance as implied by betting markets(which I adjust upwards to 42% based on my own evaluation), I get say 47.5-50% chance of Dem’s having 51+ senators. 6) I don’t have a clear sense of what are the chances of exactly 50 senators each, but betting markets seem to imply about a 15-20% chance. The House race, as it stands, is not very contentious. The Republicans would need to win not only their projected safe, likely, and leaning seats, but also all toss-ups and Dem-leaning seats as well as 11 of the 25 seats currently projected as "likely" for the Democrats just to tie. So I put it at about a 95% chance the Democrats keep the House. The senate is much more interesting. In recent years, no party has kept the Senate for more than 4 years, with Republicans keeping it on average for 2.67 terms. Over the past 30 elections, the Senate has only flipped five times, but each of those flips has come in the past 16 cycles, meaning the chance of a flip is around 30% in the modern era. However, there have only been six elections in the past 30 years where a swing of more than four seats in either direction ended up changing the majority party, and large swings have become less frequent in recent years. Moreover, recent polling shows Republicans hold more "safe" and "likely" seats than Democrats, meaning Dems would have to win around 80% of the toss-up/leaning seats to gain the majority without the VP. However, polling has been trending consistently in favor of the Democrats in recent months, meaning that possibility is not negligible. So I give them a 30% chance of winning the Senate in November.

The Republicans have no coherent, unifying strategy. President Trump has started drawing rebukes from incumbent Republicans seeking to distance themselves from him while loyalists are now confronting the problem of his record on coronavirus and Civil Rights protest response. Trump has attempted to divert attention from his coronavirus failings by focusing on quelling Civil Rights protests. This is increasingly backfiring as people realize Trump's calls for law and order come under his administration's failure to maintain law and order. Consequently, it is unlikely that Republicans will retake the gerrymandered House of Representatives by picking up any marginal districts that were lost in 2018. The possibility of Trump's strategy working is most likely to be found in Republicans retaining Senate seats in "red states." The question of how the votes play-out will depend largely on Joe Biden's actions. Thus far, Biden's strategy has been to let Trump be Trump; and this has led to a legitimate lead for Biden in national polls and apparent leads in state polls across "battleground states" and even in to Florida, Texas, and Arizona. If Biden can continue to sail the vast middle channel of the political spectrum with non-controversial policies and a non-controversial pick for vice president, Trump will have to generate momentum internally, and this is something that he has thus far been unable to do in 2020. On the other hand, if Biden has a series of gaffes or controversial policy proposals, these may not sink his chances to be president, but they may tilt Senate races against him and preserve the majority for Republicans. Given Biden's discipline thus far, I rate this as a 1-in-3 chance, with some of the likelihood that red seats will remain red (Graham remaining Senator in South Carolina, for example) subsumed.

The House is a lock for Democrats. So Senate control is the real question. Currently, polls (RealClearPolitics/fivethirtyeight) suggest that 46 Senate seats are safe/lean Democratic. 48 Senate seats are safe/lean Republican. That leaves 6 toss up states. So for Republicans to maintain control of the Senate they need either (i) 2 Senate seats from the 6 toss ups AND the Vice Presidency (Trump re-election), OR (ii) 3 Senate seats from the 6 toss ups (and Trump doesn't have to be re-elected). For Democrats to gain control of the Senate they need either (i) 4 Senate seats from the 6 toss ups AND the Vice Presidency (Biden election), OR (ii) 5 Senate seats from the 6 toss ups (and Biden doesn't have to be elected). Given the pandemic, tanking economy, and Trumps corresponding declines in the polls in key swing states (Fla, NC, Mich, etc) I currently give Joe Biden a 75% chance of taking the White House (historically re-election is tied to how the economy is performing at the time of election, and there's record levels of unemployment). When it comes to the 6 toss-up Senate seats (CO, IA, ME, NC, MI, and MT)...I have 4 of them leaning Democratic (my assigned probabilities, given current polls, are CO-D at 95% probability, ME-D at 62% probability, MI-D at 70% probability, and MT-D at 52% probability), with IA and NC being toss-ups (my assigned probabilities, given current polls at 50%-50%). With those assigned probabilities that gives Democrats about a 63% probability of winning 4 of those 6 toss ups. This 63% plus my assigned 75% probability of a Biden victory (meaning a Democratic VP will break ties in the Senate) should then impel me to increase the probability of Democrats taking control of both House and Senate to about 69%. But I've made this a little bit more conservative given two factors: (i) we're still over 4.5 months away from the election (and in a very volatile political/economic moment), and (ii) the Senate doesn't typically change control that often and even usually has a slight Republican/rural bias. So I brought down this 69% to a 63% probability that Demcrats take the House AND the Senate, with the remaining 37% that Democrats retain the House and Republicans retain the Senate.

With a 53-to-47 margin, more must go right for the Democrats than for the Republicans. Warren Buffett once said, "I don't look to jump over 7-foot bars: I look around for 1-foot bars that I can step over". It is not that Democrats cannot win the Senate -I assume they will maintain control of the House-, but that they have to jump over a 7-foot bar to do so and the Republicans have the easier task of jumping over a 1-foot bar. To take control, Democrats need a net gain of 4 seats or 3 seats plus the vice-president's tie-breaking vote. Added to this difficulty, the Senate electoral map does not favour the Democrats: the seats up for grabs already lean-Republican, so a conservative estimate would assume that the Republicans do enough to keep control. It's not a slam dunk: the Republicans are spread wide, defending 23 of the 35 seats on the ballot, so in terms of who has a chance to flip a seat, the Democrats are more likely. Election forecasters Inside Elections, Sabato’s Crystal Ball and The Cook Political Report currently rate Democrats’ opportunities to pick up seats more favorably than Republicans’. Again, Republicans have a margin of error.
